Lazy.js, with ES6 arrow functions:<p><pre><code>  var Lazy = require(&#x27;lazy.js&#x27;);

  var total = Lazy
    .generate(i => i + 1)
    .map(i => i * i)
    .take(10)
    .sum();
</code></pre>
C#, with LINQ:<p><pre><code>  IEnumerable<int> NaturalNumbers()
  {
    var i = 1;

    while (true)
      yield return i++;
  }

  var total = NaturalNumbers().Select(n => n * n).Take(10).Sum();
</code></pre>
As, of course, int has a maximum, it would be more sensible to use:<p><pre><code>  Enumerable.Range(1, int.MaxValue).Select(n => n * n).Take(10).Sum();
</code></pre>
And if you already know that you want 10, as in the above, you&#x27;d likely do:<p><pre><code>  Enumerable.Range(1, 10).Select(n => n * n).Sum();</code></pre>
